HOUSE RESOLUTION NO. 253
BY REPRESENTATIVE OWEN
A RESOLUTION
To create the Task Force on Residential Construction Cost and Inspection Practices, to study
and make recommendations regarding the impact of post-2005 building code
additions and inspection requirements on the cost of residential construction in this
state.
WHEREAS, homeowners, homebuilders, and the public have expressed concern that
onerous and inconsistent inspection regimes increase housing costs without commensurate
gains in public safety, while also creating uncertainty and financial risk for both builders and
buyers; and
WHEREAS, the Louisiana State Uniform Construction Code was originally enacted
pursuant to Act No. 12 of the 2005 First Extraordinary Session with the clear legislative
intent to limit mandatory requirements for one- and two-family dwellings to basic building
integrity and life-safety standards; and
WHEREAS, since Hurricanes Katrina and Rita, many parishes and municipalities
have imposed additional and often conflicting code requirements, energy-efficiency
mandates, inspection regimes, and permitting processes that were never contemplated in the
original 2005 law; and
WHEREAS, these additional requirements have driven significant inflation in the
cost of constructing an average single-family home in this state and have created wide
disparities in inspection fees, timelines, and enforcement practices across different regions
of the state; and
WHEREAS, the legislature finds that a comprehensive, data-driven study is
necessary to quantify the increase in the average cost of building an average home since
