2005, to document geographic disparities in inspection costs and practices, and to determine
whether new legislation is needed to protect home buyers, home builders, and public safety
while restoring the original limited scope of the residential building code.
THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED that the House of Representatives of the
Legislature of Louisiana does hereby establish the Task Force on Residential Construction
Cost and Inspection Practices to study the impact of additions and amendments to the
building codes and inspection requirements since 2005 on the cost of residential construction
in this state, and provide that this Task Force may propose recommendations, together with
specific proposals for legislation. Any recommendations or proposals shall be submitted by
written report to the legislature and to the David R. Poynter Legislative Research Library as
required by R.S. 24:771 and 772.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the legislature recommends that the task force
include consideration of all of the following:
(1) The average cost of constructing an average single-family home in Louisiana
from 2005 to the present, including a breakdown of how code and inspection requirements
have contributed to those costs.
(2) Disparities in inspection fees, permitting timelines, and enforcement practices
among parishes and municipalities, with particular attention to differences that emerged after
Hurricanes Katrina and Rita.
(3) Whether current law adequately protects home buyers, home builders, and public
safety, and whether legislation is needed to reaffirm the original intent of Act No. 12 of the
2005 First Extraordinary Session of the Legislature, limit mandatory residential requirements
to core integrity and safety standards, address inspection cost disparities, and reduce
unnecessary regulatory burdens.
(4) A list of legislative recommendations that the task force proposes to affect both
near- and long-term change for homeowners, homebuilders, and the economy of the this
state.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the task force shall consist of the following
members:
(1) Five members of the Louisiana State Uniform Construction Code Council
appointed by the chairman of the council.
